        <title><m>\S VIII.4</m>: Substitution</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Substitution</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            We will continue learning methods for finding more complicated antiderivatives.
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                
                </exercise>

                <exercise workspace="4in">
                    <title>The Chain Rule and Integration</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            Note that <m>\displaystyle \int e^{0.5x} \quad dx \neq e^{0.5x} +C</m>. Why?
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            The derivative of the right hand side requires the chain rule. In general, recall that 
                            <me>
                                \frac{d}{dx}(f(g(x))) = f'(g(x))\cdot g'(x)
                            </me>,
                            or equivalently
                            <me>
                                \int f'(g(x)) g'(x) \quad dx = f(g(x)) +C
                            </me>.
                            This gives us a strategy for finding antiderivatives using <term>substitution</term>.
                            
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>

            </page>

            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>A First Example</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int x^3 \cdot \sin(7x^4 + 3) \quad dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Letting <m>u = 7x^4 + 3</m>, our integral reduces to the <m>du</m> integral
                            <me>
                                \int \sin(u) \cdot \frac{1}{28} \quad du
                            </me>, 
                            which is easier. We compute this integral to be <m>-\frac{1}{28}\cos(u) +C</m>, and then 
                            back-substitute <m>u = 7x^4 + 3</m> to get the final answer of 
                            <me>
                                \int x^3 \cdot \sin(7x^4 + 3) \quad dx = -\frac{1}{28}\cos(7x^4 + 3) +C
                            </me>.
                            
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise>
                    <title>Practice: Substitution</title>
                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{x^2}{5x^3+1} \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u = 5x^3 +1</m>. After substituting and solving we should compute 
                                <me>
                                    \int \frac{x^2}{5x^3+1} \quad dx = \frac{1}{15} \ln|5x^3 +1| +C
                                </me>.
                                
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int e^x \sin(e^x) \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u = e^x</m>. After substituting and solving we should compute 
                                <me>
                                    \int e^x \sin(e^x) \quad dx = -\cos(e^x) +C
                                </me>.
                                
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>

                    <task workspace="2in">
                        <statement>
                            <p>
                                <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{\cos(\sqrt{x})}{\sqrt{x}} \quad dx</m>
                            </p>
                        </statement>

                        <solution>
                            <p>
                                Choose <m>u = \sqrt{x}</m>. After substituting and solving we should compute 
                                <me>
                                    \int \frac{\cos(\sqrt{x})}{\sqrt{x}} \quad dx =2 \sin(\sqrt{x})+C
                                </me>.
                                
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </task>
                    
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>
            <page>
                <exercise>
                    <title>A Final Example</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            <m>\displaystyle \int \tan(x) \quad dx</m>
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>
                            Recognizing that <m>\tan(x) = \frac{\sin(x)}{\cos(x)}</m>, the two real choice are either
                            <m>u=\sin(x)</m> or <m>u=\cos(x)</m>. The choice that will work is <m>u=\cos(x)</m>, and should
                            give us
                            <me>
                                 \int \tan(x) \quad dx = -\ln|\cos(x)| + C
                            </me>.
                            
                        </p>
                    </solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

